WEBVTT

00:07.716 --> 00:10.135
<i>At night,</i>
<i>the brightest reflection in the skies</i>

00:10.218 --> 00:14.139
<i>over New York comes from the area</i>
<i>around Times Square and Broadway.</i>

00:14.222 --> 00:16.516
<i>Thousands</i>
<i>of pleasure-seekers, like moths,</i>

00:16.599 --> 00:17.892
<i>are lured to its light.</i>

00:17.976 --> 00:20.478
<i>These sights and sounds are only a part</i>

00:20.562 --> 00:23.898
<i>of</i> <i>one of the most astonishing</i>
<i>and complicated areas in the world.</i>

00:26.985 --> 00:29.404
The whole world
is attracted to Times Square.

00:29.904 --> 00:32.866
They're entranced
and a little bit drunk off all the lights

00:32.949 --> 00:34.909
and all of the show business.

00:35.535 --> 00:40.290
But tourists don't know
what was there 45 years ago.

00:44.586 --> 00:46.504
In the late '70s,

00:46.588 --> 00:49.257
Times Square was considered an atrocity.

00:51.009 --> 00:54.971
Times Square was
a very sexually-charged atmosphere.

00:55.930 --> 00:58.641
The whole scene was something to see

00:58.725 --> 01:01.394
because it was, like,
out of Dante's<i> Inferno.</i>

01:04.314 --> 01:09.360
There were guys walking around out there
that were pure predators.

01:10.320 --> 01:13.782
The fear behind that was palpable.

01:13.865 --> 01:14.991
You could feel it.

01:17.577 --> 01:18.995
It's not easy to find a newscast

01:19.079 --> 01:21.372
with no reference
to violence and murder these days,

01:21.456 --> 01:23.750
but this week got off
to an unusually violent start

01:23.833 --> 01:25.126
right here in Midtown Manhattan.

01:27.879 --> 01:33.593
I was in the 10th Precinct
in Manhattan covering Times Square,

01:33.676 --> 01:36.054
just, uh, a uniform cop on patrol.

01:39.099 --> 01:41.351
This was December of '79,

01:41.434 --> 01:44.395
and we're stopped at a light
at 42nd Street

01:45.396 --> 01:51.486
when we saw fire trucks parked
in front of the Travel Inn hotel.

01:59.202 --> 02:00.620
When we pulled up,

02:01.246 --> 02:03.123
they excitedly said,

02:03.623 --> 02:05.583
"You better go up to the fourth floor."

02:13.049 --> 02:16.052
There was a fire in room 417.

02:17.512 --> 02:22.976
Rescue Company 1 was told that
there were likely guests inside the room.

02:24.561 --> 02:27.939
So you had the smell from burning flesh,

02:28.022 --> 02:30.316
and the smoke was thick.

02:32.152 --> 02:35.530
They crawled into the room,
not being able to see.

02:39.951 --> 02:44.831
They made out the shape
of bodies on the twin beds.

02:48.084 --> 02:52.213
One of the firemen went to give CPR…

02:56.885 --> 02:59.846
but she had no head or hands.

03:01.222 --> 03:04.267
Knocked him back
against the wall, naturally.

03:05.435 --> 03:08.813
The sergeant turned to me, and he said,

03:09.898 --> 03:12.066
"A real sick bastard did this."

03:44.515 --> 03:48.228
Firemen were first to arrive
at the scene at about 9:30 this morning.

03:49.437 --> 03:52.941
They were responding to a report
of a fire in a West Side hotel room.

03:54.525 --> 03:56.903
They found much more
than they had anticipated.

03:57.987 --> 04:00.990
Two women were found decapitated,
their hands cut off as well.

04:03.785 --> 04:06.746
Did it seem
that the women had been killed recently

04:06.829 --> 04:08.122
when you arrived?

04:08.206 --> 04:10.291
I would say so, yeah,
within a couple hours.

04:10.375 --> 04:12.835
It seems the suspect
tried to cover his tracks

04:12.919 --> 04:14.754
by setting the two beds on fire.

04:14.837 --> 04:16.881
Two separate fires,
two separate mattresses,

04:16.965 --> 04:18.049
two separate beds.

04:18.132 --> 04:19.050
For how long?

04:19.759 --> 04:21.010
Five minutes, tops.

04:30.270 --> 04:34.274
I spent 31 and a half years
with the New York City Police Department.

04:38.653 --> 04:40.780
You wouldn't believe the things I've seen.

04:42.907 --> 04:45.285
And for something to stand out,

04:45.368 --> 04:50.331
it's gotta be really bad. It has to be
absolutely horrifying to stand out.

04:50.415 --> 04:51.874
And this case did stand out.

04:54.419 --> 04:57.714
It was pretty much
the hotel room from hell.

05:01.759 --> 05:05.680
I saw the headlines before I got
the information from the NYPD,

05:05.763 --> 05:08.141
and the case immediately intrigued me.

05:10.101 --> 05:13.396
I'm a homicide and forensic expert
and consultant.

05:13.479 --> 05:15.565
I'm the former commander
of Bronx Homicide.

05:17.692 --> 05:19.485
At the time, I called up Jerry McQueen,

05:19.569 --> 05:22.864
who was the detective sergeant
who was in charge of the investigation,

05:22.947 --> 05:25.366
and he basically filled me in
what they had.

05:29.037 --> 05:31.914
The immediate problem
for the investigators was…

05:33.916 --> 05:35.710
"Who are these victims?"

05:40.048 --> 05:41.841
The first thing
you look for is fingerprints,

05:41.924 --> 05:45.053
but in this case, you were deprived
of fingerprints 'cause there's no hands.

05:46.471 --> 05:50.058
Our first inclination is that
he wants to prevent identification.

05:50.141 --> 05:52.060
That's why the heads and hands are gone.

05:52.977 --> 05:54.228
We had nothing else.

05:54.312 --> 05:56.939
No wallet, no ID, no identification cards.

05:57.982 --> 06:00.276
And don't forget, it's… it's 1979.

06:00.360 --> 06:03.404
We don't have all this video surveillance
that we have today, okay?

06:03.488 --> 06:05.073
We don't have DNA technology.

06:05.156 --> 06:08.326
It won't-- DNA technology won't come up
for another seven years.

06:09.035 --> 06:10.203
Very frustrating.

06:13.289 --> 06:19.128
The firemen said that
they felt it was a poorly conceived fire,

06:19.212 --> 06:24.175
more likely to draw attention to the room

06:24.258 --> 06:26.427
than it was to do any damage.

06:27.095 --> 06:29.764
In fact, one detective said to me

06:29.847 --> 06:32.183
it was the cleanest crime scene
he's ever seen.

06:32.850 --> 06:35.228
It was totally devoid of evidence.

06:37.021 --> 06:41.734
Spatter, gore, puddles,
fingerprints, there was nothing.

06:42.360 --> 06:44.654
How… how can you behead two women,

06:44.737 --> 06:47.073
chop off the… the hands of two women,

06:47.156 --> 06:50.743
and not have gore
from one end to the other?

06:52.453 --> 06:56.541
I did see the clothing
from the victims

06:56.624 --> 07:00.336
was piled neatly in the bathtub.

07:02.296 --> 07:04.549
You know, it seemed strange
to me at the time.

07:06.551 --> 07:08.928
<i>This killer went</i>
<i>to great lengths to destroy</i>

07:09.011 --> 07:10.346
<i>the women's identities.</i>

07:10.430 --> 07:13.141
<i>So why would he leave behind</i>
<i>the women's clothing?</i>

07:13.224 --> 07:16.227
<i>Possibly they were his gimmicks,</i>
<i>planted there,</i>

07:16.310 --> 07:18.646
<i>like the little fire he started Sunday.</i>

07:20.231 --> 07:22.275
One of the maids
from the fourth floor,

07:22.358 --> 07:26.279
uh, discovered smoke
coming from under the door

07:26.988 --> 07:31.742
and, uh, trying to open the door
to, uh, get in there.

07:31.826 --> 07:34.245
Had anybody heard
any kind of a struggle?

07:34.328 --> 07:35.830
Any noise in that room?

07:35.913 --> 07:39.292
It was don't disturb.
Don't disturb. That's all.

07:41.043 --> 07:43.880
The don't disturb sign,
was that up all along?

07:45.131 --> 07:45.965
Yes.

07:52.180 --> 07:56.100
The offender came in
on November 29th into that hotel,

07:56.726 --> 07:59.145
and he did not leave till December 2nd.

08:00.938 --> 08:02.523
A period of three days.

08:04.609 --> 08:07.570
He very cleverly signed in
as a Carl Wilson

08:07.653 --> 08:09.530
from Maryland, New Jersey,

08:10.907 --> 08:12.283
which was a fake name.

08:13.326 --> 08:16.287
The only time he was seen
was at registration.

08:21.292 --> 08:26.464
A woman stood behind him
as the subject was registering.

08:27.798 --> 08:30.426
He was alone. She was alone.

08:32.595 --> 08:35.223
But for whatever reason,
she paid attention…

08:37.683 --> 08:40.978
and they drew a composite
from her description.

08:44.649 --> 08:47.360
<i>This is the sketch</i>
<i>of the man wanted for questioning.</i>

08:47.443 --> 08:51.113
<i>He's white, 35 years old,</i>
<i>about 5'10" tall,</i>

08:51.197 --> 08:53.741
<i>and weighing 175 pounds.</i>

08:53.824 --> 08:56.369
<i>They say he has brown hair,</i>
<i>which is blow-dried.</i>

08:56.452 --> 09:00.998
<i>By that, they told me they mean this man</i>
<i>is very meticulous about his appearance.</i>

09:02.833 --> 09:05.962
In a case like this,
the police have an uphill battle

09:06.045 --> 09:09.757
because of the location
down in Times Square.

09:11.842 --> 09:16.681
Back then, it was rampant crime
of every description going on

09:17.390 --> 09:20.851
on every block,
on every corner, in every alleyway.

09:22.687 --> 09:26.566
This was a place
where someone could go unnoticed.

09:28.734 --> 09:32.989
When you're looking for a killer
in 1970s Times Square,

09:34.156 --> 09:37.577
you're looking for a needle in a haystack.

09:42.832 --> 09:46.752
There was more of a crowd in Times Square
than anywhere else in the city.

09:50.631 --> 09:52.008
There were tourists,

09:53.134 --> 09:54.802
countless businessmen…

09:55.303 --> 09:57.763
Yes, sir, what can I do for you, buddy?
What do you need today?

09:57.847 --> 10:00.558
…hustlers and three-card monte guys.

10:01.058 --> 10:03.352
Guys right out of Rikers Island.

10:06.022 --> 10:08.649
When you have the entire world
passing through,

10:09.817 --> 10:11.569
anybody could be in there.

10:14.322 --> 10:15.573
It's a hustle and bustle

10:15.656 --> 10:18.659
that's unparalleled
anywhere else in this country.

10:21.454 --> 10:24.040
I spent my entire twenties

10:24.123 --> 10:26.876
in the 1970s and '80s in Times Square.

10:27.668 --> 10:31.589
I was a writer covering the neighborhood
for men's magazines.

10:32.632 --> 10:35.926
There's probably no "official"
official designation

10:36.010 --> 10:39.138
of exactly to the foot
which makes up Times Square…

10:40.473 --> 10:45.645
…but because it's in my blood,
and I've spent so many years there

10:46.896 --> 10:49.940
between 42nd Street and 50th Street,

10:51.108 --> 10:54.070
between 8th Avenue and 6th Avenue.

10:54.987 --> 10:56.489
Those 13 blocks,

10:56.572 --> 10:59.450
that's my definition of Times Square.

11:02.078 --> 11:04.413
"The Deuce" was a nickname
at the time.

11:04.497 --> 11:07.583
It really referred to 42nd Street itself,

11:07.667 --> 11:11.921
particularly between 7th and 8th Avenue,
which is really the heart of Times Square.

11:13.506 --> 11:18.344
At its peak, it was a meeting place.
It was a place of entertainment.

11:18.427 --> 11:21.305
It was part
of the central business district.

11:21.806 --> 11:24.725
Almost all subway lines
come to Times Square.

11:25.351 --> 11:28.688
The Port Authority Bus Terminal
brings people from New Jersey

11:28.771 --> 11:30.690
but also people from around the country.

11:31.857 --> 11:34.193
For me,
it's always been a destination.

11:35.069 --> 11:37.363
I remember coming here and seeing

11:37.446 --> 11:39.657
the Camel ad where
the guy blows smoke rings.

11:41.325 --> 11:42.702
That was so cool.

11:42.785 --> 11:46.539
I mean, anything else
paled in comparison to that.

11:48.207 --> 11:52.545
There were Broadway shows,
and theaters were bustling,

11:53.129 --> 11:56.507
and it was like an element
of being in the Wild West.

11:56.590 --> 11:58.926
You know, where you didn't know
what was gonna happen,

11:59.009 --> 12:01.595
and you were going there
because you wanted to have an adventure.

12:03.055 --> 12:05.975
Times Square 42nd Street
was a collecting point…

12:07.977 --> 12:11.313
for all sorts of people.
It was like a… like a drain, you know?

12:11.397 --> 12:12.857
Everything came there.

12:18.279 --> 12:21.198
You have those
who are the denizens of the Deuce,

12:21.282 --> 12:23.576
who have lived there, they worked there,

12:23.659 --> 12:25.077
they partied there.

12:28.873 --> 12:32.960
But you have all these newcomers
who did not learn to be street-smart.

12:34.378 --> 12:37.882
And if you are not used
to being in a place

12:37.965 --> 12:40.676
where there are so many people
bumping up against you,

12:40.760 --> 12:42.470
so many lights, loud music,

12:42.553 --> 12:44.221
everything else,

12:44.305 --> 12:46.891
it's easy to become a victim

12:46.974 --> 12:49.769
because there were bad people out there.

12:58.277 --> 13:00.863
<i>For the past two weeks,</i>
<i>we've told you about the hunt</i>

13:00.946 --> 13:04.366
<i>for whoever murdered and decapitated</i>
<i>two women in the Times Square hotel.</i>

13:04.450 --> 13:07.244
<i>Authorities are asking anyone</i>
<i>with information about this man</i>

13:07.328 --> 13:08.829
<i>to call a special number.</i>

13:12.458 --> 13:16.587
The media put out
a composite sketch of a potential suspect,

13:18.255 --> 13:21.717
but at the time,
that sketch didn't help the investigation.

13:23.677 --> 13:25.304
Because nobody came forward.

13:25.888 --> 13:26.806
Very frustrating.

13:28.724 --> 13:31.435
<i>Police have had</i>
<i>to resort to the barest of evidence</i>

13:31.519 --> 13:34.313
<i>as a means of tracking down</i>
<i>the victims' identities.</i>

13:34.897 --> 13:36.440
<i>Over at the 20th Precinct,</i>

13:36.524 --> 13:39.401
<i>we saw the sorry remains</i>
<i>of the two young women.</i>

13:39.485 --> 13:42.571
<i>A pair of Bonjour jeans size 7/8,</i>

13:42.655 --> 13:45.199
<i>a pair of patent leather boots,</i>
<i>a red sweater,</i>

13:45.282 --> 13:47.910
<i>a black fur jacket waist-length,</i>

13:47.993 --> 13:49.662
<i>a pair of white leotards,</i>

13:49.745 --> 13:51.997
<i>and a pair of black high-heeled shoes.</i>

13:57.795 --> 14:00.714
Now, in order
to try to identify the victims,

14:00.798 --> 14:04.468
the investigators came up with the idea
of why don't we take these clothes

14:04.552 --> 14:06.929
that had been left behind
in the hotel room

14:07.012 --> 14:09.557
and see if we get some feedback
from the general public?

14:10.933 --> 14:12.268
One of the detectives said,

14:12.351 --> 14:15.062
"Listen, in Midtown,
we have all these department stores."

14:16.939 --> 14:20.317
"Why don't we get mannequins
from the department store

14:20.401 --> 14:22.528
and dress the mannequin in the clothing

14:24.280 --> 14:28.367
to see if anyone could identify these gals
based on the clothing?"

14:29.076 --> 14:31.912
Police tell us
they'll call a press conference tomorrow.

14:31.996 --> 14:34.039
The purpose is to dress up some mannequins

14:34.123 --> 14:36.458
with the same clothes
they showed us last week.

14:43.382 --> 14:45.634
So the mannequins were dressed,

14:46.343 --> 14:47.469
photographed,

14:49.179 --> 14:51.599
and circulars went up all over the place.

14:53.100 --> 14:56.270
They were in the newspaper.
They were on television.

14:56.854 --> 14:58.772
They were at 42nd Street.

14:59.356 --> 15:00.983
They were on light poles.

15:02.484 --> 15:06.030
Wherever you could stick
a poster with that, they were there.

15:06.530 --> 15:08.616
If you recognize
the victim's clothing,

15:08.699 --> 15:11.285
or if you have any information
that might help the police,

15:11.368 --> 15:14.038
the number to call is 477-74--

15:25.174 --> 15:27.051
In 1979,

15:27.927 --> 15:29.678
I was a crime reporter.

15:33.807 --> 15:35.017
I had covered crime,

15:35.768 --> 15:38.062
but I had never covered crime

15:38.145 --> 15:40.356
as salacious and as evil

15:40.439 --> 15:42.149
and as, uh…

15:42.232 --> 15:43.400
brutal, really.

15:44.693 --> 15:47.696
I got to know the detectives on this case

15:48.697 --> 15:51.241
and took a lot of interest
in what they were doing.

15:53.494 --> 15:58.332
And finally, they were given a tip
about one of the victims.

16:02.795 --> 16:05.464
A woman named Rose
called the police

16:06.757 --> 16:11.929
and said, "I recognize the outfit
that you have put on the television

16:12.012 --> 16:14.765
in regards to this woman."

16:14.848 --> 16:16.850
"These were my friend's clothes."

16:18.268 --> 16:21.605
She said it was the outfit and shoes

16:22.272 --> 16:24.400
her friend left the house in.

16:26.568 --> 16:29.655
Although police apparently aren't close
to making any arrests,

16:29.738 --> 16:31.281
they had a major break today

16:31.365 --> 16:33.659
when they managed to identify
one of the victims.

16:34.535 --> 16:36.537
<i>Police called on</i>
<i>the public for assistance</i>

16:36.620 --> 16:38.455
<i>and received numerous phone calls.</i>

16:39.206 --> 16:42.793
<i>One of these calls was part of the process</i>
<i>which led to identification.</i>

16:42.876 --> 16:44.294
<i>Medical records were checked,</i>

16:44.378 --> 16:47.089
<i>and identification</i>
<i>came from distinguishing characteristics</i>

16:47.172 --> 16:49.508
<i>of certain bones and scars on the body.</i>

16:50.134 --> 16:51.927
If you feel the back of your neck,

16:52.011 --> 16:56.056
uh, there are bony prominences
that can be noted,

16:56.140 --> 16:59.476
and those had
a very characteristic, uh, shape.

17:00.060 --> 17:03.355
It's on that basis
that the identification was made.

17:10.612 --> 17:12.698
One of the victims from the Travel Inn

17:12.781 --> 17:15.826
was identified as Deedeh Goodarzi,

17:15.909 --> 17:19.413
who… was my birth mother.

17:23.500 --> 17:26.253
I was adopted…

17:28.756 --> 17:30.090
at ten weeks.

17:31.550 --> 17:32.968
When I was a child,

17:33.052 --> 17:36.180
being adopted
was difficult for me to understand.

17:37.014 --> 17:40.893
I was an unknown.
I don't know where I came from.

17:42.019 --> 17:44.772
I wanted to find my biological mother.

17:49.860 --> 17:52.237
When I turned 26,

17:52.321 --> 17:54.656
I found the orphanage that I came from.

17:55.449 --> 17:58.202
And they said,
"We would love it if you came to see us."

17:58.285 --> 18:02.081
"We have a file for you to look through."

18:05.000 --> 18:09.588
I was expecting a Lifetime movie

18:09.671 --> 18:14.802
where I would get to meet, possibly,
the woman who gave birth to me.

18:17.387 --> 18:18.722
But they gave me

18:20.015 --> 18:24.937
these terrible newspaper articles
about how she was killed.

18:30.400 --> 18:34.321
There was a gorgeous picture
of my mother.

18:35.948 --> 18:36.907
So…

18:39.827 --> 18:43.664
half of me is so excited
to see my mother's face,

18:45.040 --> 18:46.375
and then feeling angry…

18:47.459 --> 18:52.673
…because her life was taken
in such a horrific manner.

18:54.049 --> 18:56.301
It's just, uh, inconceivable.

19:02.349 --> 19:06.854
Deedeh's life started in Iran.

19:09.523 --> 19:15.279
She came to America when she was
around eight or nine, and she

19:15.362 --> 19:18.365
went to Holy Family School in Brooklyn,

19:18.448 --> 19:21.160
but she never finished high school.

19:22.578 --> 19:24.663
She had run away a couple times.

19:26.957 --> 19:31.336
When she became a young adult,
she moved to Trenton, New Jersey,

19:31.420 --> 19:33.338
and I came to find out

19:33.422 --> 19:37.176
that she would take the train
on the weekends to New York City…

19:39.887 --> 19:42.931
…and she was a sex worker there.

19:46.935 --> 19:50.814
Deedeh was considered
a high-priced escort.

19:51.648 --> 19:56.695
She was working in bars,
working at massage parlors.

19:57.613 --> 20:03.660
She was the type of sex worker
that only had a couple clients in one day.

20:07.706 --> 20:09.958
The last time anyone
but her killer saw her alive

20:10.042 --> 20:12.669
was when she was in Trenton
getting on a train for New York

20:12.753 --> 20:14.630
just two days before
she was found murdered.

20:14.713 --> 20:18.175
<i>Police are still looking</i>
<i>for information about the other victim.</i>

20:18.258 --> 20:21.303
Is it your impression that these two women
might have worked together?

20:21.386 --> 20:24.473
I feel that she did, uh,
meet with the unidentified girl

20:24.556 --> 20:26.016
here in the New York City area.

20:28.185 --> 20:29.728
It's still a mystery

20:29.811 --> 20:34.024
how Deedeh Goodarzi ended up
in that room with the other girl.

20:35.108 --> 20:38.737
The other girl we know nothing about.
Not a thing.

20:40.530 --> 20:42.241
She remained a Jane Doe.

20:43.909 --> 20:46.578
But based on Deedeh being a prostitute,

20:46.662 --> 20:51.083
these detectives thought the other victim
was likely a prostitute as well.

20:58.799 --> 21:02.219
The area of Times Square
near the Travel Inn

21:03.762 --> 21:06.390
had become known for sex workers…

21:09.601 --> 21:11.770
who worked the streets,

21:11.853 --> 21:14.356
who worked the hotels,
who worked the bars.

